05533nam a22006855i 9780226493237DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212005ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264932377 a10.7208/97802264932372doi  a(DE-B1597)575567  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBQ4040b.C75 2005eb 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a294.3/0722200aCritical Terms for the Study of Buddhism /cDonald S. Lopez Jr. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuddhism and Modernity00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Impressions of the Buddha -- tContributors -- tBuddha -- tArt -- tDeath -- tEconomy -- tGift -- tHistory -- tInstitution -- tPedagogy -- tPerson -- tPower -- tPractice -- tRitual -- tSex -- tWord -- tModernity -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past century, Buddhism has come to be seen as a world religion, exceeding Christianity in longevity and, according to many, philosophical wisdom. Buddhism has also increasingly been described as strongly ethical, devoted to nonviolence, and dedicated to bringing an end to human suffering. And because it places such a strong emphasis on rational analysis, Buddhism is considered more compatible with science than the other great religions. As such, Buddhism has been embraced in the West, both as an alternative religion and as an alternative to religion. This volume provides a unique introduction to Buddhism by examining categories essential for a nuanced understanding of its traditions. Each of the fifteen essays here shows students how a fundamental term-from art to word-illuminates the practice of Buddhism, both in traditional Buddhist societies and in the realms of modernity. Apart from Buddha, the list of terms in this collection deliberately includes none that are intrinsic to the religion. Instead, the contributors explore terms that are important for many fields and that invite interdisciplinary reflection. Through incisive discussions of topics ranging from practice, power, and pedagogy to ritual, history, sex, and death, the authors offer new directions for the understanding of Buddhism, taking constructive and sometimes polemical positions in an effort both to demonstrate the shortcomings of assumptions about the religion and the potential power of revisionary approaches. Following the tradition of Critical Terms for Religious Studies, this volume is not only an invaluable resource for the classroom but one that belongs on the short list of essential books for anyone seriously interested in Buddhism and Asian religions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aBuddhismxPhilosophy. 0aBuddhismxStudy and teaching. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aAbé, Ryūichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenavides, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielefeldt, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrook, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyatso, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvy, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJr, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJr., Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLachman, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopez Jr., Donald S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 